issues.title: Fix Syntax Error and Add AppVars to get_schema
issues.body:
@KitHensel, CC: @liquidise @zsiglin 

It looks like commit af4a56d937f8591c719b804eae35be05d702aa29 introduced a syntax error in the QuickBase gem. This could potentially break many of your gem users out there.

Also, our app has a lot of application vars so calling `get_db_var` for each is rather inefficient when we can just use `get_schema` to grab them all at once.

This PR fixes the syntax error and adds appvars to the get_schema response.

Current `get_schema` response:
```ruby
{
 :app_id=>"example_table_id",
 :table_id=>"example_table_id",
 :name=>"My Example App",
 :mode=>"app",
 :tables=> {"dbid"=>{:dbid=>"example", :name=>"Applications"}}
}
```

New `get_schema` response:
```ruby
{
 :app_id=>"example_table_id",
 :table_id=>"example_table_id",
 :name=>"My Example App",
 :mode=>"app",
 :tables=> {"dbid"=>{:dbid=>"example", :name=>"Applications"}},
 :variables => {
    "EXAMPLE_VAR_1" => "some_value",
    "EXAMPLE_VAR_2" => "some_value"
 }
}
```

Any ETA on when we might be able to get this merged? Thanks in advance!

issues.title: Raise exception if the HTTP request fail
issues.body:
If a request to Quickbase API fails with HTTP status code other than 200, the send_request method returns the xml of returned error page (404 or 500 pages etc).
It should have raised an exception in this case.
I have called `result.value` right after the request so that it would raise Net::HTTPServerException if HTTP status code is not 200.

issues.title: HTTP response status code should be checked
issues.body: This gem works great. But if for some reason quickbase is down or not available for a request, then this gem doesnt raise any exception and returns nil or empty array depending on the method called. Like if we call do_query method, and for some reason the request fails with 404 or 500 status code. Then the method will return an empty array instead of raising an exception or something.

issues.title: Fixed do_query method when called without fmt paramater
issues.body:
`record.css('f')` is used to loop over the fields returned in the do_query with fmt parameter.
`record.element_children` is used to loop over the fields returned in do_query without fmt parameter.

the if condition
`if options.has_key :fmt`
should be stated before looping over the fields, so to know if `record.css('f')` should be used or `record.element_children`

issue_comments.body:
I have made another commit. This will not break the default behavior of do_query method.

The following should also be added in the documentation of this gem.

To call do_query API without `<fmt>structured</fmt>`, pass `fmt: nil` or `fmt: ''` in options while calling `do_query` method.
`AdvantageQuickbase::API.new(domain, username, password, apptoken).do_query( db_id, {fmt: nil})`
or
`AdvantageQuickbase::API.new(domain, username, password, apptoken).do_query( db_id, {fmt: ''})`
The above examples will return unstructured data.

Not passing `fmt` or passing `fmt: (anything)` will result in calling API with `<fmt>structured</fmt>`
`AdvantageQuickbase::API.new(domain, username, password, apptoken).do_query( db_id, {})`
or
`AdvantageQuickbase::API.new(domain, username, password, apptoken).do_query( db_id, {fmt: 'xyz'})`
The above examples will return structured data.

@liquidise 
I think you have forgot to merge the changes done in version 0.8.4 and 0.8.5, you have only updated the version number in gemspec due to which this repo and gem (https://rubygems.org/gems/advantage_quickbase) codebase has deviated.

example:
http://www.rubydoc.info/gems/advantage_quickbase/0.8.5/AdvantageQuickbase/API:do_query
Click on `view source` and see the line 92 of quickbase.rb of the gem codebase

And now the line 92 of quickbase.rb of this repo
https://github.com/AdvantageIntegratedSolutions/Quickbase-Gem/blob/master/lib/quickbase.rb#L92

I already made a pull request.
I thought to update the ReadMe but then I realized it would be better if you update it yourself, to make it more understandable that,
`query_options` expects `fmt` as well.. Though by default `fmt: 'structured'`,
for unstructured data use `fmt: nil` or `fmt: ''`

@liquidise , do check my https://github.com/AdvantageIntegratedSolutions/Quickbase-Gem/issues/2#issuecomment-68333024 before releasing on rubygems.
Just pushed gem version 0.9.0 that includes your patch. Thanks!
